  "prompt": "How and when ISS was send to space?",
  "response": "The International Space Station (ISS) is a joint project involving multiple space agencies, including NASA, Roscosmos, JAXA, ESA, and CSA. The assembly of the ISS began with the launch of the first module, Zarya, which was sent into space by Russia on November 20, 1998. \n\nFollowing the launch of Zarya, the U.S. module Unity was launched aboard Space Shuttle Endeavour on December 4, 1998, and docked with Zarya two days later. Over the next several years, additional modules and components were sent into space and added to the ISS through a series of shuttle missions and other launches by various partner agencies.\n\nThe construction and assembly of the ISS involved numerous missions and was completed over a decade, with the station gradually becoming operational and habitable. Astronauts began living and working on the ISS on a rotating basis starting in November 2000, and it has been continuously occupied since then.\n\nThe ISS continues to serve as a space laboratory where scientific research in a microgravity environment is conducted, supporting international collaboration in space exploration.",
